<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 11 — Replacement Rules

  Draft status:
  - Building section by section.
  - Introduces the ten replacement rules as logical equivalences.
  - Distinguishes replacement rules from implication rules on two axes:
    bidirectionality and applicability to subformulas.
  - Proof examples use the same compact answer-key style as Chapter 10.
  - Conditional proof and indirect proof are deferred to a later chapter.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-replacement-rules">

  <title>Replacement Rules</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-replacement-rules-intro">
    <p>
      If you worked through the proofs in Chapter 10, you probably
      had a moment — maybe several — where you could <em>see</em>
      what needed to happen next but could not make any of the eight
      implication rules do it. You had a negated conjunction and
      needed a disjunction. You had a conditional and needed a
      disjunction. You had a line that was <em>almost</em> the right
      shape to trigger Modus Ponens, except one piece was written
      in the wrong form. You stared at it. The rules stared back.
      Nobody moved.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter fixes that. The ten <term>replacement rules</term>
      let you rewrite a statement into a logically equivalent form.
      Where the implication rules let you derive <em>new</em>
      statements from old ones, replacement rules let you
      <em>reshape</em> a statement you already have, trading it for a
      version that says the same thing in different logical clothing.
      Once you can reshape, the implication rules can do their work on
      the reshaped line, and proofs that were stuck become unstuck.
    </p>
    <p>
      Together, the eight implication rules from Chapter 10 and the
      ten replacement rules from this chapter form the eighteen-rule
      natural deduction system used in this course. With all eighteen
      in hand, every valid sentential argument can be proven valid.
      (We will add two more tools — Conditional Proof and Indirect
      Proof — in the next chapter, but those are strategies for
      organizing proofs, not new rules of inference.)
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-replacement-vs-implication">
    <title>What Replacement Rules Are</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Before we list the ten rules, we need to understand what
        makes them different from the eight implication rules. The
        difference is not cosmetic. It changes how you read a rule,
        how you apply it, and what mistakes to watch for.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-differences">
      <title>Two differences that matter</title>
      <p>
        Implication rules and replacement rules differ on exactly two
        axes.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Difference 1: Direction.</alert> An implication rule is
        a one-way street. Modus Ponens lets you go from
        <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m> and
        <m>\mathcal{A}</m> to <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. It does not let you
        go backward. You cannot start with <m>\mathcal{B}</m> and
        recover <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>. The arrow
        points in one direction, and you follow it.
      </p>
      <p>
        A replacement rule is a two-way street. It states a logical
        equivalence: two forms that have the same truth value on every
        row of every truth table. Because the equivalence holds in
        both directions, you may replace either side with the other
        whenever you need to.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Difference 2: Scope.</alert> An implication rule
        applies only to <em>whole lines</em>. When you use Modus
        Ponens, the entire line must match
        <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>, and the entire other
        line must match <m>\mathcal{A}</m>. You cannot reach inside a
        larger formula and apply MP to a piece of it.
      </p>
      <p>
        A replacement rule can apply to a <em>part</em> of a line.
        If a subformula of a line matches one side of a replacement
        rule, you may replace that subformula with the other side,
        leaving the rest of the line untouched. This is powerful. It
        means replacement rules can reshape the interior of a complex
        formula without dismantling the whole thing first.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-replacement-example-motivation">
      <title>Why this matters: a motivating example</title>
      <p>
        Consider this argument:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-motivation">
        <title>An argument the implication rules cannot handle</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: <m>P \supset Q</m></p>
          <p>P2: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m></p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Try proving this with only the eight implication rules from
        Chapter 10. Modus Tollens gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> from lines 1 and 2. Good.
        Addition gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m> from
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. Done — that particular
        path works. But suppose instead that the conclusion were just
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m> and your only
        premise were <m>P \supset Q</m>. No second premise. No way to
        apply MT. No way to get <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> by
        itself. The implication rules cannot rewrite
        <m>P \supset Q</m> into
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m>, even though a
        truth table confirms the two are logically equivalent.
      </p>
      <p>
        A replacement rule called <em>Material Implication</em> does
        exactly that rewrite, in one step. That is what replacement
        rules are for: they bridge the gap between forms that are
        logically equivalent but syntactically different.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-replacement-justification-format">
      <title>How to cite a replacement rule</title>
      <p>
        The justification format is the same as for implication rules:
        cite the line number and the rule abbreviation. Because
        replacement rules apply to a single line (rewriting it into an
        equivalent form), the justification always cites exactly one
        earlier line.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-replacement-justification-example">
        <title>A Replacement Rule Justification</title>
        <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
          <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
          <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m></cell><cell>1 Impl</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Line 2 rewrites line 1 using Material Implication. The
        justification says: line 1, by Impl. One line cited, one rule
        named.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-replacement-common-mistakes">
      <title>Two mistakes to avoid from the start</title>
      <p>
        Students make two predictable errors when they first encounter
        the eighteen-rule system.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Mistake 1: Using an implication rule
        backward.</alert> Modus Ponens lets you go from
        <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m> and
        <m>\mathcal{A}</m> to <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. It does
        <em>not</em> let you go from <m>\mathcal{B}</m> to
        <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>. Implication rules
        are one-way. If you catch yourself writing a line that
        goes <q>backward</q> through an implication rule, stop.
        Only replacement rules work in both directions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Mistake 2: Applying a replacement rule to only part
        of a line and thinking you used an implication
        rule.</alert> If you replaced a subformula inside a larger
        formula, you used a replacement rule. Implication rules do
        not work on parts of lines. If you aren't sure which kind
        of rule you used, ask: did I rewrite something into an
        equivalent form, or did I derive something new? Rewriting
        is replacement. Deriving is implication.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ten-replacement-rules">
    <title>The Ten Replacement Rules</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Each rule below is a logical equivalence. Read the double
        bar between the two sides as <q>is logically equivalent
        to.</q> You may replace either side with the other, in
        either direction, on a whole line or on a subformula within
        a line.
      </p>
      <p>
        As in Chapter 10, the metavariables
        <m>\mathcal{A}</m>, <m>\mathcal{B}</m>, <m>\mathcal{C}</m>
        stand for any well-formed formulas. The same metavariable
        must be replaced by the same formula throughout a single
        application of the rule.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-dem">
      <title>De Morgan's Theorems (DeM)</title>
      <p>
        <term>De Morgan's Theorems</term> tell you how negation
        distributes across conjunctions and disjunctions. A negated
        conjunction becomes a disjunction of negations, and a negated
        disjunction becomes a conjunction of negations.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-dem">
        <title>De Morgan's Theorems Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B})</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A} \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B})</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        De Morgan's is probably the replacement rule you will use
        most. Whenever you see a negation sign sitting in front of a
        parenthesized conjunction or disjunction, De Morgan's is
        likely the next move. The pattern is: the negation
        <q>passes through</q> the parentheses, flipping the
        connective as it goes. <em>And</em> becomes <em>or</em>;
        <em>or</em> becomes <em>and</em>; each component picks up
        its own negation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Students sometimes try to distribute a negation without
        flipping the connective:
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m> does <em>not</em>
        become
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.
        It becomes
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.
        The flip is not optional. If the connective does not change,
        the equivalence does not hold. (Build the truth table if you
        don't believe it. The table will settle the argument faster
        than I can.)
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-dn">
      <title>Double Negation (DN)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Double Negation</term> says that two negations cancel.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-dn">
        <title>Double Negation Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        We previewed this rule in Chapter 10 when we needed to apply
        Modus Tollens to a line whose consequent was already negated.
        DN lets you add or remove a double negation whenever you need
        to. It is a small rule, but it comes up constantly — often as
        the last step before another rule can fire.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-com">
      <title>Commutation (Com)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Commutation</term> says that the order of conjuncts or
        disjuncts does not matter.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-com">
        <title>Commutation Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>\mathcal{B} \cdot \mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>\mathcal{B} \lor \mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Commutation does not apply to conditionals.
        <m>P \supset Q</m> is not equivalent to
        <m>Q \supset P</m>. (If it were, affirming the consequent
        would be a valid move, and Chapter 3 would owe you an
        apology.)
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-assoc">
      <title>Association (Assoc)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Association</term> lets you regroup parentheses around
        conjunctions or disjunctions.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-assoc">
        <title>Association Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \cdot (\mathcal{B} \cdot \mathcal{C})</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}) \cdot \mathcal{C}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \lor (\mathcal{B} \lor \mathcal{C})</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}) \lor \mathcal{C}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Like Commutation, Association does not apply to conditionals.
        You will use it most often to rearrange a three-part
        conjunction or disjunction so that Simplification or
        Disjunctive Syllogism can reach the piece you need.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-dist">
      <title>Distribution (Dist)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Distribution</term> lets you distribute a connective
        across another, much as multiplication distributes over
        addition in arithmetic.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-dist">
        <title>Distribution Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \cdot (\mathcal{B} \lor \mathcal{C})</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}) \lor (\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{C})</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \lor (\mathcal{B} \cdot \mathcal{C})</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}) \cdot (\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{C})</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Distribution is the hardest of the algebraic rules to spot
        in practice. Unlike Commutation and Association, which feel
        natural, Distribution changes the shape of a formula
        dramatically. A conjunction of a letter and a disjunction
        becomes a disjunction of two conjunctions, and vice versa.
        The arithmetic analogy helps:
        <m>a \times (b + c) = (a \times b) + (a \times c)</m>. The
        dot is the logical <q>times</q> and the wedge is the logical
        <q>plus.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-trans">
      <title>Transposition (Trans)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Transposition</term> — sometimes called
        <em>contraposition</em> — swaps the antecedent and
        consequent of a conditional while negating both.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-trans">
        <title>Transposition Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B} \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        You already know this equivalence from Chapter 3, where we
        observed that Modus Tollens runs a conditional <q>in
        reverse.</q> Transposition makes that move explicit: the
        contrapositive of a conditional is logically equivalent to
        the original. Use it when a proof needs the conditional
        turned around so that Modus Ponens, rather than Modus
        Tollens, can apply.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-impl">
      <title>Material Implication (Impl)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Material Implication</term> trades a conditional for a
        disjunction and back.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-impl">
        <title>Material Implication Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        This is the rule we motivated in
        <xref ref="sec-replacement-vs-implication"/>. It says that
        <q>if <m>\mathcal{A}</m> then <m>\mathcal{B}</m></q> is
        equivalent to <q>either not-<m>\mathcal{A}</m> or
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.</q> That equivalence might look strange,
        but it falls directly out of the conditional truth table from
        Chapter 9: the conditional is false only on the TF row, and
        so is the disjunction
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Material Implication is especially useful when you need to
        convert a conditional into a form that can interact with De
        Morgan's, Distribution, or Disjunctive Syllogism.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-equiv">
      <title>Material Equivalence (Equiv)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Material Equivalence</term> unpacks a biconditional
        into its component parts. There are two equivalent ways to
        unpack it.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-equiv">
        <title>Material Equivalence Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \equiv \mathcal{B}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}) \cdot (\mathcal{B} \supset \mathcal{A})</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \equiv \mathcal{B}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}) \lor ({\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B})</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The first form says: a biconditional is a conjunction of two
        conditionals, one in each direction. The second form says: a
        biconditional is true when both sides match — both true or
        both false. Choose whichever form gives you something you can
        work with. Usually the first form is more useful, because it
        gives you conditionals that Modus Ponens and Modus Tollens
        can act on.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-exp">
      <title>Exportation (Exp)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Exportation</term> moves a conjunct out of the
        antecedent of a conditional and into a nested conditional,
        or vice versa.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-exp">
        <title>Exportation Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>(\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}) \supset \mathcal{C}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset (\mathcal{B} \supset \mathcal{C})</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        This rule says: <q>if <m>\mathcal{A}</m> and
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m>, then <m>\mathcal{C}</m></q> is equivalent
        to <q>if <m>\mathcal{A}</m>, then if <m>\mathcal{B}</m> then
        <m>\mathcal{C}</m>.</q> The conjunction in the antecedent
        gets <q>exported</q> into a chain of two conditionals. Use
        Exportation when you have part of an antecedent available and
        want to peel it off.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rule-taut">
      <title>Tautology (Taut)</title>
      <p>
        <term>Tautology</term> lets you collapse or introduce a
        redundant repetition.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-taut">
        <title>Tautology Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell><cell><m>\Leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Tautology is the rule that looks the least useful on first
        contact. Why would you ever need to replace <m>P</m> with
        <m>P \lor P</m>? Because sometimes a proof produces a
        disjunction like <m>P \lor P</m> through Constructive
        Dilemma or some other path, and you need to collapse it back
        to <m>P</m>. In the other direction, you might need a
        disjunction to feed into another rule, and the only material
        available is a bare statement. Tautology lets you
        manufacture the disjunction. It is a small tool that
        occasionally saves a proof from an otherwise dead end.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ten-rules-summary">
      <title>Ten rules at a glance</title>
      <p>
        Here are all ten replacement rules with their abbreviations,
        for reference:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-ten-rules-summary">
        <title>The Ten Replacement Rules</title>
        <tabular halign="left">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Rule</cell>
            <cell>Abbreviation</cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell>De Morgan's Theorems</cell><cell>DeM</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Double Negation</cell><cell>DN</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Commutation</cell><cell>Com</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Association</cell><cell>Assoc</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Distribution</cell><cell>Dist</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Transposition</cell><cell>Trans</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Material Implication</cell><cell>Impl</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Material Equivalence</cell><cell>Equiv</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Exportation</cell><cell>Exp</cell></row>
          <row><cell>Tautology</cell><cell>Taut</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Together with the eight implication rules from Chapter 10
        (MP, MT, HS, DS, Simp, Conj, Add, CD), these ten rules form
        the complete eighteen-rule natural deduction system for
        sentential logic. Every valid sentential argument can be
        proven valid using some combination of these eighteen rules.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-replacement-appendix-reference">
      <title>Quick reference</title>
      <p>
        All ten replacement rules — together with the eight
        implication rules from the previous chapter — are collected
        in <xref ref="appendix-rules-of-inference"/> for quick
        reference. Keep that appendix handy as you work through
        proofs.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-worked-proofs-replacement">
    <title>Worked Proofs</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The proofs in Chapter 10 used only implication rules. The
        proofs below mix implication and replacement rules. In each
        case the replacement rules do the reshaping — converting a
        formula into an equivalent form — so that an implication rule
        can finish the job. If you read the proofs and feel like the
        replacement step <q>came out of nowhere,</q> go back to the
        rule schema in §11.2 and confirm that the two sides really
        are equivalent. You should not have to take anyone's word for
        it; you can always build the truth table.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-proof-1">
      <title>Proof 1: De Morgan's into Simplification</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-1">
        <title>Using De Morgan's to extract a negation</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-1">
            <title>Deriving <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>1 DeM</cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>3 Simp</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Line 1 is a negated disjunction. None of the implication rules
        can act on it directly. De Morgan's rewrites it as a
        conjunction of negations (line 3), and then Simplification
        pulls out the piece we need (line 4). Two steps, and the
        proof is done.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that line 2 was never used. That is fine. Premises
        are available, not required. A proof is valid as long as
        every derived line follows from earlier lines by a legitimate
        rule. (Unused premises are common in exercises. They test
        whether you can identify the path that matters, rather than
        blindly using everything in sight.)
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-proof-2">
      <title>Proof 2: Material Implication into Disjunctive Syllogism</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-2">
        <title>Converting a conditional to use DS</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-2">
            <title>Deriving <m>Q</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \lor R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>2,3 DS</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,4 MP</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This proof uses only implication rules and serves as a
        baseline. Now consider what happens if the premises are
        rearranged so that no implication rule fires directly:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-2b">
        <title>The same argument, rearranged</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-2b">
            <title>Deriving <m>Q</m> using Impl</title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,2 MP</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        That one was trivial — MP handles it in one step. But what
        if the conclusion were
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m> instead?
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-2c">
        <title>Reaching a disjunction via Impl</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-2c">
            <title>Deriving <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m></cell><cell>1 Impl</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Material Implication does the entire job: it rewrites the
        conditional as an equivalent disjunction. One line, one rule.
        This is the motivating example from §11.1, now completed as a
        proof.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-proof-3">
      <title>Proof 3: Transposition and De Morgan's together</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-3">
        <title>Chaining two replacement rules</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-3">
            <title>Deriving <m>R</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}({\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}R)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>R</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>2 DeM</cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>Q \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>3 DN</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>Q \cdot R</m></cell><cell>4 DN</cell></row>
              <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>R</m></cell><cell>5 Simp</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Line 2 is a negated disjunction of two negations. That is
        exactly the kind of expression that makes you stare at the
        page. But the procedure is straightforward: De Morgan's breaks
        it open (line 3), and then we need two applications of Double
        Negation — one for each double-negated component. Line 4
        removes the double negation from
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>,
        and line 5 removes it from
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m>.
        Simplification finishes (line 6).
      </p>
      <p>
        A note on lines 4 and 5: we applied DN once per line,
        cleaning up one double-negated component at a time. This is
        the convention we follow in this course — one application of
        one rule per line. Some instructors allow applying DN to
        both components in a single step, collapsing lines 4 and 5
        into one line. Check with your instructor if you are unsure
        which convention your course uses.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-proof-4">
      <title>Proof 4: A longer proof mixing both rule types</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-4">
        <title>A five-premise proof</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-4">
            <title>Deriving <m>S</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>S</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell>1 Exp</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>R</m></cell><cell>3,4 MP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>S</m></cell><cell>2,5 MP</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Line 1 is a nested conditional: <q>if <m>P</m>, then if
        <m>Q</m> then <m>R</m>.</q> We have both <m>P</m> and
        <m>Q</m> in line 3, but not separately — they are packaged
        as a conjunction. Exportation (line 4) rewrites the nested
        conditional so that the conjunction
        <m>P \cdot Q</m> is the antecedent. Now MP can fire with
        lines 3 and 4, giving <m>R</m> (line 5). A second MP with
        line 2 finishes the proof.
      </p>
      <p>
        Without Exportation, this proof would require separating
        <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> by Simplification, applying MP twice
        on the nested conditional, and taking more steps to reach the
        same place. Replacement rules often shorten proofs by making
        formulas match the shapes that implication rules expect.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-proof-5">
      <title>Proof 5: Distribution and Material Implication</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-replacement-proof-5">
        <title>A proof requiring Distribution</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-replacement-proof-5">
            <title>Deriving <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor R</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \supset Q) \cdot (P \supset R)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor R</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell>1 Simp</cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell><cell>1 Simp</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>2,3 MT</cell></row>
              <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor R</m></cell><cell>5 Add</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This proof did not need Distribution after all — Simplification
        and Modus Tollens did the work. That is a useful lesson in
        itself: do not reach for a complex replacement rule when a
        simpler path is available. The best proof is usually the
        shortest one. Distribution exists for cases where the formula
        cannot be broken apart by other means, not for every proof
        that happens to contain a conjunction and a disjunction.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-11-3-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Compare two proof paths</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose one of the proof exercises from this chapter that
          you completed. Now try to prove the same argument a
          <em>different</em> way — using a different replacement
          rule at a key step, or starting from a different premise.
          Write both proofs out. Which is shorter? Which felt more
          natural? Did the second attempt teach you anything about
          the argument that the first one didn't?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-replacement-strategy">
    <title>Strategy for Replacement Rules</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Chapter 10 offered a set of habits for finding proofs:
        look at the target, mine the premises, work backward.
        Those habits still apply. But now you have eighteen rules
        instead of eight, and the question <q>which rule should I
        try?</q> has become harder. This section gives you
        pattern-matching shortcuts — not a recipe, but a set of
        <q>if you see this shape, try this rule</q> heuristics that
        will save you time.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-trigger-patterns">
      <title>Trigger patterns</title>
      <p>
        Each replacement rule has a characteristic shape that
        should trigger it in your mind. Here are the most common:
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Negation in front of parentheses:</alert> Try
        <em>De Morgan's</em>. If you see
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(\ldots)</m> where the
        parentheses contain a conjunction or disjunction, DeM is
        almost certainly your next step. This is the single most
        common trigger in student proofs.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Double tilde:</alert> Try <em>Double Negation</em>.
        If any part of a line has
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m>
        sitting in front of it, remove it. DN is almost never a
        bad move. In the rare case where you need to <em>add</em>
        a double negation, it is usually because you need to set
        up Modus Tollens or De Morgan's on a subsequent line.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>A conditional where you need a disjunction (or vice
        versa):</alert> Try <em>Material Implication</em>. Impl
        converts between <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>
        and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}</m>.
        If the conclusion is a disjunction and your premises are
        all conditionals, Impl is likely in the proof.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>A conditional whose antecedent and consequent are
        in the wrong order:</alert> Try <em>Transposition</em>.
        If you have <m>P \supset Q</m> but need
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>
        to set up a Hypothetical Syllogism chain, Trans rewrites
        the conditional as its contrapositive.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>A biconditional:</alert> Try <em>Material
        Equivalence</em>. No implication rule can act on a
        biconditional directly. Equiv unpacks it into two
        conditionals (joined by a conjunction) or into the
        <q>matching truth values</q> form. You must use Equiv
        before you can do anything else with a biconditional.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>A nested conditional with a conjunction available
        (or a conjoined antecedent with components
        available):</alert> Try <em>Exportation</em>. Exp converts
        between <m>(\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}) \supset \mathcal{C}</m>
        and <m>\mathcal{A} \supset (\mathcal{B} \supset \mathcal{C})</m>.
        It shows up less often than DeM or Impl, but when you need
        it, nothing else will do.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Conjuncts or disjuncts in the wrong order:</alert>
        Try <em>Commutation</em>. This is a housekeeping move.
        You will rarely plan a proof around Commutation, but you
        will sometimes need it so that a formula matches the shape
        required by another rule or by the target.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Parentheses grouped inconveniently:</alert> Try
        <em>Association</em>. Like Commutation, this is
        housekeeping — regrouping a three-part conjunction or
        disjunction so that Simplification or DS can reach the
        component you need.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-when-distribution">
      <title>When to use Distribution</title>
      <p>
        Distribution deserves its own note because students either
        overuse it or forget it exists. Here is a simple test: if
        your formula is a conjunction of a letter and a disjunction
        (or a disjunction of a letter and a conjunction), and no
        simpler rule breaks it apart, Distribution is probably the
        move. If Simplification, DS, or MP can already extract
        what you need, skip Distribution.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same applies to Tautology. You will not need it often.
        When you do, it is usually because the proof produced
        <m>P \lor P</m> or <m>P \cdot P</m> and you need to
        collapse it to <m>P</m>. Outside of that cleanup role,
        leave Tautology on the shelf.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-replacement-strategy-order">
      <title>A general order of operations</title>
      <p>
        When you sit down with a proof and are not sure where to
        begin, try this sequence:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Look at the conclusion.</alert> What is its main
          connective? What components does it contain? This tells
          you what you need to produce.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Scan the premises for the conclusion's
          components.</alert> Are they present, perhaps in a
          different form? If a component appears negated, inside a
          conditional, or buried in a conjunction, a replacement
          rule may extract or reshape it.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Identify the gap.</alert> What is the difference
          between what you have and what you need? If it is a shape
          difference — the right content in the wrong connective
          — a replacement rule bridges it. If it is a content
          difference — you need a letter that does not appear
          anywhere — an implication rule derives it.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Work backward from the conclusion.</alert> What
          rule would produce the conclusion in one step? What
          would its input need to look like? Can you produce that
          input from the premises? This backward-chaining habit
          from Chapter 10 is even more valuable now, because
          replacement rules give you more ways to reshape inputs
          into the forms the implication rules expect.
        </p></li>
      </ol>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-replacement-common-errors">
      <title>Common errors revisited</title>
      <p>
        Now that you have seen proofs in action, here are the
        errors that show up most often on student work. Knowing
        them in advance will not prevent all mistakes, but it may
        help you catch them before you hand anything in.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Forgetting to flip the connective in De
        Morgan's.</alert> This is the single most common error in
        the entire course. When the negation passes through the
        parentheses, the dot becomes a wedge and the wedge becomes
        a dot. Every time. No exceptions. If you write a De
        Morgan's step and the connective did not change, erase it
        and try again.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Applying Commutation or Association to a
        conditional.</alert> Conditionals are not commutative.
        <m>P \supset Q</m> is not equivalent to
        <m>Q \supset P</m>. If you need to reverse a conditional,
        use Transposition (which negates both sides) or Material
        Implication (which converts to a disjunction). Do not swap
        the antecedent and consequent and hope for the best.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Using an implication rule on a subformula.</alert>
        Only replacement rules apply to parts of lines. If you
        tried to use Modus Ponens on a conditional that appears
        <em>inside</em> a larger formula, you have made an error.
        Extract the conditional first (perhaps by Simplification),
        then apply MP.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Citing the wrong rule name.</alert> This sounds
        minor, but on a graded proof it costs points. If you
        rewrote a conditional as a disjunction, the rule is Impl,
        not DeM. If you swapped the order of two disjuncts, the
        rule is Com, not Assoc. The abbreviations are short and
        specific. Use the reference table in §11.2 until the names
        become automatic.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-replacement-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      With eighteen rules in hand you can prove every valid
      sentential argument — in principle. In practice, some proofs
      are difficult to find because the conclusion does not appear
      in the premises at all, even in disguise. The strategy
      chapters have taught you to work backward from the conclusion,
      but what do you do when the conclusion is a conditional and
      none of the premises contain its consequent?
    </p>
    <p>
      The next chapter introduces two new proof strategies:
      <em>Conditional Proof</em> and <em>Indirect Proof</em>.
      These are not new rules of inference — they do not add to
      the eighteen. Instead, they are strategies for
      <em>organizing</em> a proof. Conditional Proof lets you
      assume the antecedent of a conditional, derive its
      consequent, and then discharge the assumption to conclude
      the conditional itself. Indirect Proof lets you assume the
      negation of what you want to prove, derive a contradiction,
      and conclude that the assumption was false. Both strategies
      expand what you can prove efficiently, and both build on
      everything you have learned so far.
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch-replacement-rules">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced the ten replacement rules and
      distinguished them from the eight implication rules.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>What Replacement Rules Are (§11.1).</alert> Replacement
      rules differ from implication rules on two axes: they are
      bidirectional (logical equivalences, not one-way inferences),
      and they may be applied to subformulas within a line, not just
      to whole lines.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Ten Replacement Rules (§11.2).</alert> De Morgan's
      Theorems, Double Negation, Commutation, Association,
      Distribution, Transposition, Material Implication, Material
      Equivalence, Exportation, and Tautology. Together with the
      eight implication rules from Chapter 10, these form the
      complete eighteen-rule natural deduction system.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Worked Proofs (§11.3).</alert> Replacement rules
      reshape formulas so that implication rules can fire. Common
      patterns include De Morgan's into Simplification, Material
      Implication to convert between conditionals and disjunctions,
      and Exportation to flatten nested conditionals.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Strategy for Replacement Rules (§11.4).</alert>
      Pattern-matching heuristics help you decide which rule to try:
      negation in front of parentheses triggers De Morgan's, double
      tildes trigger DN, conditionals-to-disjunctions trigger Impl,
      and biconditionals require Equiv before anything else. A
      four-step procedure — look at the conclusion, scan for
      components, identify the gap, work backward — organizes the
      search.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch11-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-association">
        <title>Association</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that regroups parentheses around conjunctions or disjunctions. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-commutation">
        <title>Commutation</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that swaps the order of conjuncts or disjuncts. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-de-morgans">
        <title>De Morgan's Theorems</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that converts a negated conjunction into a disjunction of negations, and a negated disjunction into a conjunction of negations. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-distribution">
        <title>Distribution</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that distributes a connective across another connective, analogous to distributing multiplication over addition. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-double-negation">
        <title>Double Negation</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that adds or removes a pair of negation signs. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-exportation">
        <title>Exportation</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that converts a conditional with a conjoined antecedent into a nested conditional, and vice versa. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-material-equivalence">
        <title>Material Equivalence</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that unpacks a biconditional into a conjunction of two conditionals, or into a disjunction of matching truth-value pairs. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-material-implication">
        <title>Material Implication</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that converts a conditional into a disjunction (negated antecedent or consequent), and vice versa. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-replacement-rule">
        <title>Replacement rule</title>
        <p>A rule of inference that states a logical equivalence, allowing either side to replace the other in any direction and on any subformula within a line. (§11.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-tautology">
        <title>Tautology</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that collapses a redundant conjunction or disjunction (<m>P \cdot P</m> or <m>P \lor P</m>) into a single statement, or introduces one. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-transposition">
        <title>Transposition</title>
        <p>A replacement rule that swaps and negates the antecedent and consequent of a conditional, producing its contrapositive. Also called contraposition. (§11.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch11-trigger-pattern">
        <title>Trigger pattern</title>
        <p>A characteristic formula shape that signals which replacement rule is likely to apply. (§11.4)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch11">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch11-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identifying Replacement Rules</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each transformation, name the replacement rule that
          justifies it.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m> is replaced by <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p><m>P \supset Q</m> is replaced by <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p><m>P \supset Q</m> is replaced by <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> is replaced by <m>P</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p><m>P \lor Q</m> is replaced by <m>Q \lor P</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-06">
        <statement>
          <p><m>P \equiv Q</m> is replaced by <m>(P \supset Q) \cdot (Q \supset P)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-07">
        <statement>
          <p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m> is replaced by <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s01-08">
        <statement>
          <p><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m> is replaced by <m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch11-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Apply the Rule</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Apply the indicated replacement rule to the given formula.
          Write the result.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply DeM to <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(R \lor S)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply Impl to <m>R \supset S</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply Trans to <m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply DN to <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-05">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply Dist to <m>P \cdot (Q \lor R)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-06">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply Equiv to <m>P \equiv Q</m> (use the first form).</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-07">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply Exp to <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s02-08">
        <statement>
          <p>Apply Taut to <m>P \lor P</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch11-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Proofs Using Replacement Rules</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Prove each argument valid using the eighteen rules of
          inference (implication and replacement rules).
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-05">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \equiv Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-06">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>R \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-07">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s03-08">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch11-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Explain the Strategy</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each proof situation, write one or two sentences
          explaining which replacement rule you would try first
          and why.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>You have <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m> and need to derive <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>You have <m>P \supset Q</m> and the target is a disjunction.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>You have <m>P \supset Q</m> and need <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> for a Hypothetical Syllogism chain.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>You have <m>P \equiv Q</m> and need to extract <m>P \supset Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-s04-05">
        <statement>
          <p>You have <m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m> and <m>P \cdot Q</m> is available on an earlier line.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch11-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to Field Exercise 11-1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the two proof paths from Field Exercise 11-1.
            What makes one proof <em>better</em> than another? Is it
            length? Clarity? The feeling of inevitability? Write a
            short reflection on what you value in a proof now that
            you have built enough to compare them.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
